{{Infobox book | name = Mga Ibong Mandaragit | image = | image_caption = | author = [[Amado V. Hernandez]] | country = [[Philippines]] | language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] | genre = [[Fiction]] | media_type = | publisher = | release_date = | pages = | isbn = }}
'''''Mga Ibong Mandaragit''''' or '''''Mga Ibong Mandaragit: Nobelang Sosyo-Politikal''''' (literally, ''Birds of Prey: A Socio-Political Novel'') is a [[novel]] written by the [[Filipino people|Filipino]] writer and social activist, [[Amado V. Hernandez]] in 1969. ''Mga Ibong Mandaragit'', hailed as Hernandez's masterpiece, focuses on the [[Neocolonialism|neocolonial]] dependency and revolt in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=PhilCSC/> The novel reflects Hernandez's experience as a [[guerrilla]] intelligence officer when the Philippines was under [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]] from 1942 to 1945.<ref name=PhilCSC>[http://philcsc.wordpress.com/2008/08/26/appreciating-amado-v-hernandez-proletarian-artis/ "Mga Ibong Mandaragit" by Amado V. Hernandez], from Amado V. Hernandez: An Introduction, Appreciating Amado V. Hernandez, Revolutionary Proletarian Artist, philcsc.wordpress.com, August 28, 2006</ref>
==Description== The narrative, illustrates Hernandez's yearning for change and the elevation of the status of Philippine society and living conditions of [[Filipino people|Filipinos]]. The setting is in the middle of [[Philippines Campaign (1944–1945)|1944]], when the armed forces of the [[Japanese Empire]] were losing.<ref name=Hernandez/>
The novel acts as a sequel to [[Jose Rizal]]'s historic ''[[Noli Me Tangere (novel)|Noli Me Tangere]]'' and ''[[El filibusterismo]]''. The protagonist Mando Plaridel is tested by Tata Matyas, an old revolutionary, on his knowledge about Rizal and Rizal's novels. Similar to Rizal's novel, the main character examines the Philippines as an outsider while traveling in Europe.<ref name=Veric>Veric, Charlie Samuya. [http://www.ateneo.edu/kritikakultura/pdf/issue1/Fictions%20of%20Necessity%20by%20Charlie%20Veric.pdf "''Mga Ibong Mandaragit''" by Amado V. Hernandez] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614085048/http://www.ateneo.edu/kritikakultura/pdf/issue1/Fictions%20of%20Necessity%20by%20Charlie%20Veric.pdf |date=2011-06-14 }}, The Fictions of Necessity, Book Review of Caroline Hau’s “Necessary Fictions”, Ateneo de Manila University, ateneo.edu</ref> Hernandez's novel also tackles the lead character's search for Simoun's treasure, acting as a continuation of Rizal's ''[[El Filibusterismo]]''. The novel portrays the conditions of the citizenry at the onset of [[industrialization]] brought forth by the [[United States of America|Americans]] in the Philippines. ''Mga Ibong Mandaragit'' had been translated into [[English language|English]] and [[Russian language|Russian]].<ref name=Hernandez>Hernandez, Amado V. ''Mga Ibong Mandaragit: Nobelang Sosyo-Politikal'', with a Prologue by [[Carlos P. Romulo]] and [[Epilogue]] by [[Epifanio San Juan, Jr.]], Progressive Printing Palace, Quezon City, 1969, 416 pages.</ref>
